        <section>
            <h2>Understanding HTML Comments</h2>
   
            <p>HTML comments are not displayed in the browser but can help document your code, making it easier to understand and maintain. Comments are enclosed within <span class="highlight">&lt;!--</span> and <span class="highlight">--&gt;</span> tags.</p>
            <pre><code>&lt;!-- This is an HTML comment --&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>Comments can be used to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Explain sections of code.</li>
                <li>Hide code temporarily for debugging purposes.</li>
                <li>Provide additional information for developers.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="special-characters">
            <h2>Using Special Characters in HTML</h2>
            <p>In HTML, special characters are represented using HTML entities to ensure they display correctly. Here are some commonly used special characters and their corresponding HTML entities:</p>
            <ul>
                
                <li><strong>Ampersand (&amp;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;amp;</code> to render as: &amp;</li>
                <li><strong>Less than (&lt;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;lt;</code> to render as: &lt;</li>
                <li><strong>Greater than (&gt;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;gt;</code> to render as: &gt;</li>
                <li><strong>Copyright (&copy;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;copy;</code> to render as: &copy;</li>
                <li><strong>Registered Trademark (&reg;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;reg;</code> to render as: &reg;</li>
                <li><strong>Trademark (&trade;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;trade;</code> to render as: &trade;</li>
                <li><strong>Non-breaking space (&nbsp;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;nbsp;</code> to render as a space.</li>
                <li><strong>Euro (&euro;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;euro;</code> to render as: &euro;</li>
                <li><strong>Yen (&yen;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;yen;</code> to render as: &yen;</li>
                <li><strong>Pound (&pound;):</strong> Use <code>&amp;pound;</code> to render as: &pound;</li>
            </ul>
         
            <p>If you want to display special characters such as mathematical symbols or punctuation marks that have special meanings in HTML (like <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&gt;</code>), you must use their HTML entities to avoid rendering issues.</p>
        </section>
